        "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
        "score": 1,
        "is_accepted": false,
        "last_activity_date": 1418758557,
        "creation_date": 1418758156,
        "body": "<p>If you want full portability and a \"native terminal emulator\", you will have to code something that picks the \"right\" terminal emulator yourself. There are two commands that do a bit of choosing themselves:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>On Debian based Distro's you can use <code>x-terminal-emulator -e &lt;cmd&gt;<\/code>, however this does not work on e.g. Centos.<\/li>\n<li>FreeDesktop has <code>xdg-terminal<\/code> (<a href=\"http://cgit.freedesktop.org/xdg/xdg-utils/tree/scripts/xdg-terminal.in\" rel=\"nofollow\">code<\/a>) as part of the <code>xdg-utils<\/code> package, however the script seems not to be distributed at all. <\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>Since neither of these is guaranteed to be present, you will still have to test for availability and use xterm etc. as fall-back.<\/p>\n",
        "answer_id": 27512427,
        "question_id": 25005122,
        "last_edit_date": 1418758557
    }],
